TI  - Promoting the sustainable development of the recycling market of construction and demolition waste: A stakeholder game perspective
AU  - Su, Yangyue
AU  - Si, Hongyun
AU  - Chen, Jianguo
AU  - Wu, Guangdong
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - The government, construction contractors, and waste recycling plants are the three critical stakeholders in the construction and demolition wastes (C&DW) recycling market. However, the low efficiency of government supervision, the low quality of the recycled products, and the poor acceptance of contractors have challenged the sustainability of the market in China. This study examined how strategies are changing for local governments, contractors, and recycling plants in the C&DW recycling market by establishing a tripartite evolutionary game model. Numerical simulation analysis was used to verify the proposed theoretical model and discuss the key parameters' effects on stakeholder decision-making on the basis of current practice in Shanghai, China. The results demonstrated that: (i) six evolutionary stable strategies exist, of which the strategies combination of the supervision of market by local governments, the purchasing of recycled products by contractors, and the production of high-quality products by recycling plants are the most favourable choices. (ii) The evolutionary stable strategy of recycling plants highly depends on production cost and violation penalties. Recycling plants will be induced to produce high-quality products when violation penalties are higher than the additional cost for obeying supervision policies. (iii) The evolutionary stable strategy of construction contractors is significantly affected by product prices, reputation benefits, and resource taxes. Construction contractors are willing to pay a reasonable environmental premium for recycled products as long as the associated reputation benefits are sufficiently attractive. (iv) Lower subsidy is more conducive to evolving toward a trilateral stable strategy because of limited government finances. This study may contribute to the present understanding of the behavior, demand and synergy of stakeholders in the C&DW recycling market and provides valuable management implications for policymakers to promote the sustainable C&DW recycling practice. (C) 2020 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
DA  - 2020
PY  - 2020
