TI  - Environmental assessment of unprocessed sand-sized construction & demolition waste for geotechnical reuse
AU  - Agarwal, Apoorva
AU  - Ramana, G. V.
AU  - Datta, Manoj
AU  - Soni, Narendra Kumar
AU  - Satyakam, Rajiv
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Unprocessed construction and demolition waste may ultimately reach municipal solid waste landfills/dumpsites or incineration plants unless it is proven feasible to be reused in bulk quantities in geotechnical applications after assessing the environmental risk associated with them. In India, around 50% of unprocessed C & D waste is comprised of sand-sized fractions, and the suitability to reuse it in unbound geotechnical applications needs a physicochemical and environmental assessment. In this study, detailed laboratory testing was conducted comprising the mineralogical composition, organic content, soluble solids, and heavy metals (leachable and solid). Sampling was carried out over 3 months at a weekly interval from ten discrete locations at two processing plants to account for the variability and heterogeneity. The obtained results were compared with those of local soil, Delhi silt. The test results showed that 40-45% of sand-sized fractions comprised of silt, and the primary mineral present was silica, followed by aluminium oxide and calcium oxide. The average organic content was 2.0% and was within the regulatory limits for reuse in embankments. The environmental risk was characterised based on soluble solids and the leaching of heavy metals. The concentration levels measured were higher than those of the local soil but are within limits for inert material as per European Council Decision 2003/33/EC guidelines. Total metal concentration was five times higher than that of the local soil but satisfied the criteria for soil quality guidelines for unbound reuse adopted globally. The ecological risk due to heavy metals is insignificant due to moderate contamination levels. Therefore, the reuse of sand-sized fractions of unprocessed construction and demolition waste for unbound applications seems to be a promising avenue and an alternative to the local soil for sustainable development.
DA  - 2022
PY  - 2022
