TI  - Improving the frost resistance of recycled aggregate concrete: A comprehensive review
AU  - Zhang, Hongrui
AU  - Zheng, Rui
AU  - Wu, Gan
AU  - Yao, Yiming
AU  - Bao, Jiuwen
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - The utilization of recycled coarse aggregate (RCA) in concrete provides a sustainable and effective strategy for the disposal of construction and demolition waste and the conservation of natural resources. However, recycled aggregate concrete (RAC) is affected by the porous old mortar and multiple interfacial transition zones (ITZs). Significant deterioration occurs when it is exposed to freeze-thaw (FT) cycles. This paper presents a comprehensive review on methods to enhance the frost resistance of RAC through pre-treatment of RCA (removal of old mortar and strengthening old mortar), reinforcement of RAC (adding supplementary cementitious materials, nanomaterials, fibers, air-entraining agents) and other methods. The efficiency of different reinforcement methods was evaluated, focusing on the modification mechanisms of different methods on the frost resistance of RAC. The results indicate that both pre-treatment of RCA and reinforcement of RAC can significantly improve the frost resistance of RAC. Microwave heating, carbonization treatment, and silane emulsion immersion of RCA can reduce the mass loss rate of RAC by over 40 %. The methods such as adding supplementary cementitious materials, nanomaterials, and fibers can also reduce the mass loss rate of RAC by over 40 % or increase the relative dynamic elastic modulus by over 40 %. Moreover, the limitations and challenges of different methods are summarized, emphasizing the need to strike a balance between efficiency, cost, and environmental impact. Finally, the future research on the frost resistance of RAC is proposed to promote the widespread application of RAC in cold regions and advance the green transformation of the construction industry.
