TI  - DIGITAL TWIN-ENABLED REVERSE SUPPLY CHAIN FOR BUILDING DEMOLITION WASTE MANAGEMENT
AU  - Su, Shuaiming
AU  - Yang, Yishu
AU  - Besklubova, Svetlana
AU  - Song, Jidong
AU  - Kong, Xiang T. R.
AU  - Zhong, Ray Y.
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - The increasing volume of building demolition waste (BDW) has exerted significant pressure on the ecological environment. In response, governmental bodies, corporations, and academia have made considerable efforts in the field of BDW management. However, the recycling and reuse rates of BDW remain below expectations. This shortfall is primarily attributed to the limited digitalization across the waste disposal chain, which hinders seamless information exchange and, consequently, the efficient circulation of BDW. Additionally, the underdeveloped state of the reverse supply chain (RSC) further exacerbates this issue. To address these challenges, this study proposes a digital twin-enabled RSC as a novel paradigm for BDW management. By leveraging digital twin technology, the monitoring of BDW treatment processes and information sharing among stakeholders can be significantly enhanced, thereby laying a digital foundation for efficient resource circulation. Furthermore, by comprehensively assessing the recyclable value of BDW, a market-oriented circulation channel is explored to ensure profitability for stakeholders within the RSC. The BDW RSC is constructed based on the classic fivedimensional digital twin model. A mathematical model is developed to analyze the impact of internal and external factors within the RSC on the cost-benefit dynamics of demolition contractors. A case study, based on a real estate project in Beijing, is conducted to validate the framework. Finally, ten key implications are derived from the framework and case study to offer practical insights for stakeholders engaged in BDW RSC management.
